{"key":"processedPost-15321663","value":{"id":15321663,"first":15321578,"last":15323439,"when":1320428833,"utime":"11/04/11 08:47 PM","content":"All substrates should be consolidated after full colonization for best results.<br /><br />Furthermore, there is no reason to case horse manure.&nbsp; It fruits as well uncased, and you don't lose the ten days it takes the casing layer to colonize up through the surface, which is what you should do before introducing to fruiting conditions.&nbsp; Next time, when the manure is fully colonized, give it a week or two to allow the mycelium to digest the substrate, and then place in fruiting conditions uncased.<br />RR","title":"Re: consolidation in bulk substrates","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}